00:45:07.600 --> 00:45:09.080
On the shore of the Dead Sea

00:45:09.080 --> 00:45:14.710
in the early '70s was
discovered an ancient synagogue,

00:45:14.710 --> 00:45:16.290
it was Byzantine.

00:45:16.290 --> 00:45:18.010
And it is now a national park.

00:45:18.010 --> 00:45:20.210
So you can go there and you
could see the synagogue.

00:45:20.210 --> 00:45:21.770
It looks like this.

00:45:21.770 --> 00:45:25.620
It's a beautiful mosaic
floor covered by a tent.

00:45:25.620 --> 00:45:29.930
And in the floor was
found the holy ark.

00:45:29.930 --> 00:45:31.230
And in that holy ark is

00:45:31.230 --> 00:45:33.600
where the En-Gedi
Scroll was discovered.

00:45:33.600 --> 00:45:36.100
It was so badly damaged
that it was not possible

00:45:36.100 --> 00:45:38.130
to identify anything about it.

00:45:38.130 --> 00:45:41.700
But Sefi, the archeologist
always believed

00:45:41.700 --> 00:45:45.550
that it could hold significance.

00:45:45.550 --> 00:45:46.850
And so he told me personally

00:45:46.850 --> 00:45:48.150
when we did the press
conference,

00:45:48.150 --> 00:45:49.450
he actually thanked me.

00:45:49.450 --> 00:45:51.960
He said, "I didn't know if in
my lifetime we would ever solve

00:45:51.960 --> 00:45:53.260
this mystery."

00:45:53.260 --> 00:45:55.870
But let me show you
now the second video

00:45:55.870 --> 00:45:58.250
that actually has audio
which will explain

00:45:58.250 --> 00:46:01.560
to you the complete unwrapping
process on the En-Gedi Scroll.

00:46:01.560 --> 00:46:05.490
&gt;&gt; Virtual unwrapping begins

00:46:05.490 --> 00:46:08.370
by acquiring a three-dimensional
volumetric scan

00:46:08.370 --> 00:46:10.270
of the damaged manuscript.

00:46:10.270 --> 00:46:13.260
This scan produces a set
of cross-sectional images

00:46:13.260 --> 00:46:16.770
that show the internal
structure of the scroll.

00:46:16.770 --> 00:46:18.520
When viewed as a 3D object,

00:46:18.520 --> 00:46:21.480
one can clearly see the
individual layers of the scroll

00:46:21.480 --> 00:46:22.880
that any text on the surface

00:46:22.880 --> 00:46:25.400
of those layers is
obscured from view.

00:46:25.400 --> 00:46:28.290
In order for a readable version
of the scroll to be produced,

00:46:28.290 --> 00:46:29.860
these images must be passed

00:46:29.860 --> 00:46:33.360
through our virtual
unwrapping pipeline.

00:46:33.360 --> 00:46:36.500
First, we capture the 3D shape
of the layers of the scroll

00:46:36.500 --> 00:46:38.760
in a process called
segmentation.

00:46:38.760 --> 00:46:41.210
On the left side of the
screen, the software moves

00:46:41.210 --> 00:46:44.030
through the scroll image
by image tracing the shape

00:46:44.030 --> 00:46:45.330
of a single scroll back.

00:46:45.330 --> 00:46:48.670
On the right, we see the 3D
model that this produces.

00:46:48.670 --> 00:46:51.940
Next, we extract the
ink from the data

00:46:51.940 --> 00:46:53.850
in a process called texturing.

00:46:53.850 --> 00:46:56.890
Using the 3D shape
generated by segmentation,

00:46:56.890 --> 00:46:58.460
our software makes another pass

00:46:58.460 --> 00:47:02.170
through the scroll this time
looking for very bright pixels.

00:47:02.170 --> 00:47:05.030
Bright pixels indicate
regions of dense material.

00:47:05.030 --> 00:47:07.950
In this case, inks
made with iron or lead.

00:47:07.950 --> 00:47:10.050
We now have a single
wrap of the scroll

00:47:10.050 --> 00:47:12.630
with the text shown
clearly on its surface.

00:47:12.630 --> 00:47:15.660
However, because the surface
is curved, it's difficult

00:47:15.660 --> 00:47:18.100
to read all of the text
from one viewpoint.

00:47:18.100 --> 00:47:19.400
The flattening stage

00:47:19.400 --> 00:47:22.300
of a pipeline converts
this textured 3D surface

00:47:22.300 --> 00:47:26.450
into a flat plane so that the
text can be more easily read.

00:47:26.450 --> 00:47:28.020
To produce the best results,

00:47:28.020 --> 00:47:31.430
these three steps must be
performed on one small section

00:47:31.430 --> 00:47:33.130
of the scroll at a time.

00:47:33.130 --> 00:47:35.940
As a result, we end up
with several texture images

00:47:35.940 --> 00:47:37.660
that must be merged together.

00:47:37.660 --> 00:47:40.960
This merging process creates
a single consolidated image

00:47:40.960 --> 00:47:43.460
that shows the full text.

00:47:43.460 --> 00:47:46.700
Using this pipeline, we have
restored and revealed the text

00:47:46.700 --> 00:47:49.690
of five complete wraps
of the En-Gedi Scroll.

00:47:49.690 --> 00:47:51.090
The two distinct columns

00:47:51.090 --> 00:47:53.000
of Hebrew writing
revealed the scroll

00:47:53.000 --> 00:47:54.610
to be the book of Leviticus.

00:47:54.610 --> 00:47:57.500
This marks the En-Gedi
Scroll as the earliest copy

00:47:57.500 --> 00:48:00.330
of Pentateuchal book
ever found in a holy ark,

00:48:00.330 --> 00:48:03.610
a significant discovery
in biblical archeology.

