00:48:09.740 --> 00:48:13.510
The price was right on that deal
and also, you know, I miss her

00:48:13.510 --> 00:48:19.390
and so I'm reminded of her
when I hear her voice now.

00:48:19.390 --> 00:48:23.660
Somebody after my talk asked
me is your daughter OK thinking

00:48:23.660 --> 00:48:25.540
that maybe, you know,
is it memorial

00:48:25.540 --> 00:48:27.420
and I said, no, no she's fine.

00:48:27.420 --> 00:48:31.320
She just lives in
California, you know?

00:48:31.320 --> 00:48:32.890
When they go off to
California, you know.

00:48:32.890 --> 00:48:36.080
So here you go.

00:48:36.080 --> 00:48:39.240
This was our complete
unwrapping, five wraps,

00:48:39.240 --> 00:48:41.510
fully readable text,
known text pushed

00:48:41.510 --> 00:48:42.810
through the entire pipeline.

00:48:42.810 --> 00:48:47.160
The miracle occurred and now
the magic trick actually looks

00:48:47.160 --> 00:48:50.340
like-- it doesn't look
stupid anymore, right?

00:48:50.340 --> 00:48:53.530
Because it's complete
and we pushed

00:48:53.530 --> 00:48:56.650
through the entire pipeline
and refined each section

00:48:56.650 --> 00:48:58.640
of the pipeline to
the point we're now--

00:48:58.640 --> 00:49:00.830
we think that we're
actually ready not only

00:49:00.830 --> 00:49:03.050
to solve the technical
part of virtual unwrapping

00:49:03.050 --> 00:49:07.050
for most materials but also
to provide those materials

00:49:07.050 --> 00:49:10.660
as scholarship to scholars
who can then use the quality

00:49:10.660 --> 00:49:13.460
of our result to do, for
example, biblical scholarship.

00:49:13.460 --> 00:49:17.140
And let me tell you that we did
that with the En-Gedi Scroll

00:49:17.140 --> 00:49:20.450
and this is why it's
significant.

00:49:20.450 --> 00:49:24.720
This dating in terms of
biblical scholarship occurs

00:49:24.720 --> 00:49:28.670
between the period of the Dead
Sea Scroll second temple period,

00:49:28.670 --> 00:49:34.010
scroll from En-Gedi at 300 C.E.
and really the next witness

00:49:34.010 --> 00:49:36.270
which was 6 or 700 years later

00:49:36.270 --> 00:49:38.700
where Cairo Genizah
gives evidence

00:49:38.700 --> 00:49:43.040
of the Masoretic
text being settled.

00:49:43.040 --> 00:49:45.240
And so there was some
question about how early

00:49:45.240 --> 00:49:48.970
that Masorete text goes back
into the unsettled first

00:49:48.970 --> 00:49:50.940
and second temple period.

00:49:50.940 --> 00:49:52.560
The scholars told
me all of this.

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:54.260
I am not a biblical scholar.

00:49:54.260 --> 00:49:56.280
But look at what
we were able to do.

00:49:56.280 --> 00:50:00.040
We wrote a biblical
scholarship paper together.

00:50:00.040 --> 00:50:03.670
Michael Segal and Emanuel
Tov, giants in the field

00:50:03.670 --> 00:50:06.900
of this area, with
me as a co-author,

00:50:06.900 --> 00:50:09.050
and the reason why they
allowed me to be a co-author is

00:50:09.050 --> 00:50:12.140
because the image they
used does not exist.

00:50:12.140 --> 00:50:16.070
The image that they used
is the result of a piece

00:50:16.070 --> 00:50:18.190
of software that
we wrote, right?

00:50:18.190 --> 00:50:21.020
It's completely generated
virtually.

00:50:21.020 --> 00:50:22.770
It's not a photograph, right?

00:50:22.770 --> 00:50:26.070
It's not the result of
physically unwrapping anything.

00:50:26.070 --> 00:50:30.280
And so we were able to take that
image at a quality high enough

00:50:30.280 --> 00:50:34.510
that a paleographer and a
biblical scholar could print it

00:50:34.510 --> 00:50:37.570
out and create basically
what they would do

00:50:37.570 --> 00:50:39.820
with the photograph
of an open fragment.

00:50:39.820 --> 00:50:42.910
And then because they could
see all the letter forms,

00:50:42.910 --> 00:50:45.190
do paleography, a
complete transcription

00:50:45.190 --> 00:50:47.550
and biblical scholarship.

00:50:47.550 --> 00:50:50.770
So from the pages
to the flattening

00:50:50.770 --> 00:50:53.150
to the complete 3D unwrapping,
you see the progression

00:50:53.150 --> 00:50:55.740
of this work to the place
where now I could talk

00:50:55.740 --> 00:50:59.310
about my rousing conclusion,

00:50:59.310 --> 00:51:01.590
which is what I'm calling
reference amplification

00:51:01.590 --> 00:51:04.390
and the use of what we all
have heard off in the news

00:51:04.390 --> 00:51:07.540
in the last several
years machine learning.

00:51:07.540 --> 00:51:09.370
Now I want to tell you why
machine learning is really

00:51:09.370 --> 00:51:11.200
important because
conventional wisdom,

00:51:11.200 --> 00:51:15.350
which is almost always
wrong, which somehow I seem

00:51:15.350 --> 00:51:18.700
to always adopt, right,
tells us a few things.

00:51:18.700 --> 00:51:21.710
It tells us that well, that
scroll was probably a fluke,

00:51:21.710 --> 00:51:26.340
Seales got lucky, that's for
sure, there is obviously metal

00:51:26.340 --> 00:51:28.920
in the ink so that you could
see the signal really easily.

00:51:28.920 --> 00:51:34.240
So this probably isn't
going to have any relevance

00:51:34.240 --> 00:51:36.520
to Herculaneum because we
all know there is no metal

00:51:36.520 --> 00:51:39.170
in the ink et cetera, et
cetera, conventional wisdom.

00:51:39.170 --> 00:51:41.650
Also conventional wisdom
also tells us, you know,

00:51:41.650 --> 00:51:43.010
why couldn't it be Genesis?

00:51:43.010 --> 00:51:47.330
You know, why did it have
to be-- just as an aside.

00:51:47.330 --> 00:51:49.430
Well, it's true that there
was metal in the ink.

00:51:49.430 --> 00:51:51.050
We don't know exactly
the composition

00:51:51.050 --> 00:51:54.340
because we analyzed
everything non-invasively.

00:51:54.340 --> 00:51:59.070
But if you take a look at
the signal in this figure

00:51:59.070 --> 00:52:01.510
from our paper, you
can see really bright

00:52:01.510 --> 00:52:04.860
where the Hebrew letters are,
meaning, you know, very dense,

00:52:04.860 --> 00:52:07.900
lots denser, right, than
the surrounding material,

00:52:07.900 --> 00:52:09.650
the animal skin.

00:52:09.650 --> 00:52:13.010
So how do I answer that
conventional wisdom?

00:52:13.010 --> 00:52:17.100
I mean for the longest time, I
also believed this statement.

00:52:17.100 --> 00:52:20.420
Carbon ink is invisible
in tomography.

00:52:20.420 --> 00:52:21.720
I don't know.

00:52:21.720 --> 00:52:23.680
Those of you who know
may have heard that.

00:52:23.680 --> 00:52:28.580
But, you know, we
were doing some work

00:52:28.580 --> 00:52:32.570
at a high energy
physics facility.

00:52:32.570 --> 00:52:37.110
And whenever I hang
around bright people,

00:52:37.110 --> 00:52:39.280
they raise me up, right?

00:52:39.280 --> 00:52:40.610
Does that work for you?

00:52:40.610 --> 00:52:46.010
I don't know if I actually get
smarter or I just act smarter

00:52:46.010 --> 00:52:48.140
because they're all
smart, right?

00:52:48.140 --> 00:52:49.940
But, you know, we
started working together

00:52:49.940 --> 00:52:52.130
and I started thinking, really?

00:52:52.130 --> 00:52:53.430
Carbon is not visible?

00:52:53.430 --> 00:52:55.390
I mean, why is everything
else visible in some way,

00:52:55.390 --> 00:52:58.760
shape or form but carbon ink
on carbon is not visible?

00:52:58.760 --> 00:53:00.330
I just don't get that.

00:53:00.330 --> 00:53:02.990
So we ran some numbers and
I started to think about it.

00:53:02.990 --> 00:53:05.160
So I went back to my
kitchen and we started

00:53:05.160 --> 00:53:07.080
to do some experiments.

00:53:07.080 --> 00:53:08.520
I got out the iron gall, the--

00:53:08.520 --> 00:53:11.360
not the iron gall,
the carbon black.

00:53:11.360 --> 00:53:13.490
I ruined a few utensils.

00:53:13.490 --> 00:53:17.050
And I made some patterns.

00:53:17.050 --> 00:53:19.130
And, you know, I really gobbed
it on because I thought,

00:53:19.130 --> 00:53:21.790
you know, I'm going to
see what's going on here.

00:53:21.790 --> 00:53:24.290
And then we got a little
bit more sophisticated

00:53:24.290 --> 00:53:26.020
with some test patterns
in papyrus

00:53:26.020 --> 00:53:27.320
and some other real materials.

00:53:27.320 --> 00:53:30.260
And we started to do a
systematic study instead

00:53:30.260 --> 00:53:31.770
of just relying on
conventional wisdom.

00:53:31.770 --> 00:53:33.130
And guess what we found.

00:53:33.130 --> 00:53:38.070
Of course carbon is
visible in tomography, OK?

00:53:38.070 --> 00:53:39.370
There it is.

00:53:39.370 --> 00:53:40.690
Carbon on paper.

00:53:40.690 --> 00:53:43.230
On the left, you
see that the carbon

00:53:43.230 --> 00:53:45.510
and the paper looked
very similar in density

00:53:45.510 --> 00:53:48.160
because they're about
the same at that energy.

00:53:48.160 --> 00:53:50.480
And on the right, you see that
the paper is much brighter

00:53:50.480 --> 00:53:52.590
than the carbon at
the other energy.

00:53:52.590 --> 00:53:55.870
And we can actually look at
this, different energies,

00:53:55.870 --> 00:53:59.630
different contrasts
between the two.

00:53:59.630 --> 00:54:02.180
Then I did an experiment
with some students,

00:54:02.180 --> 00:54:07.260
where I asked them to write up
some-- make up some proxies.

00:54:07.260 --> 00:54:10.810
And this student decided--
Allie decided that she was going

00:54:10.810 --> 00:54:18.200
to put carbon black on papyrus--
excuse me, on parchment.

00:54:18.200 --> 00:54:20.870
We hadn't really
done that before,

00:54:20.870 --> 00:54:22.940
carbon black on parchment.

00:54:22.940 --> 00:54:27.340
Most of the ink we've seen
on parchment are in Gaul.

00:54:27.340 --> 00:54:30.330
So she did that.

00:54:30.330 --> 00:54:32.030
And she scanned it.

00:54:32.030 --> 00:54:34.410
And she ran our tool
to unwrap it virtually

00:54:34.410 --> 00:54:36.690
and then she showed
us the result.

00:54:36.690 --> 00:54:40.400
And there was a delta in Carbon.

00:54:40.400 --> 00:54:41.840
Why can you see it?

00:54:41.840 --> 00:54:46.130
It's supposed to be invisible
in tomography, right?

00:54:46.130 --> 00:54:48.180
Well, we did a little
bit of work and found

00:54:48.180 --> 00:54:51.180
that what's actually going on
is that you can see the carbon

00:54:51.180 --> 00:54:53.130
but you have to have the
right resolution and you have

00:54:53.130 --> 00:54:57.160
to tease it out from
the underlying pattern

00:54:57.160 --> 00:55:01.450
of whatever the structure
is that the carbon is on.

00:55:01.450 --> 00:55:04.900
If it's on papyrus, you end
up with this fiber pattern

00:55:04.900 --> 00:55:07.820
that is really hard
for your eye, you know,

00:55:07.820 --> 00:55:12.220
to see the difference when
there's carbon on there.

00:55:12.220 --> 00:55:15.850
Papyrus has that fiber
structure but parchment doesn't.

00:55:15.850 --> 00:55:19.600
And the reason that Allie was
able to see the carbon ink

00:55:19.600 --> 00:55:23.590
on the parchment was because
the parchment was really smooth,

00:55:23.590 --> 00:55:25.450
right, and then you get
that carbon on there,

00:55:25.450 --> 00:55:27.100
you could see it straight away.

00:55:27.100 --> 00:55:30.530
So we actually started
to do some experiments

00:55:30.530 --> 00:55:34.870
where we took carbon
ink on papyrus

00:55:34.870 --> 00:55:37.810
and we developed a framework
for being able to tease

00:55:37.810 --> 00:55:41.250
out what you can't
see with the eye.

00:55:41.250 --> 00:55:42.550
And we used machine
learning to do it.

00:55:42.550 --> 00:55:43.850
And I'll be showing you one

00:55:43.850 --> 00:55:45.820
of the first examples
and then I'll finish.

00:55:45.820 --> 00:55:47.830
On the left you see
a test pattern.

00:55:47.830 --> 00:55:52.140
Six, 5, 4 at the top is six
codes, five codes, four codes.

00:55:52.140 --> 00:55:53.800
Real scientific, right?

00:55:53.800 --> 00:55:58.170
On the right, you see the
tomography to give you a sense

00:55:58.170 --> 00:56:00.640
of what you can see with the
naked eye and what you can't.

00:56:00.640 --> 00:56:03.920
On the left column with six
coats, you can actually see,

00:56:03.920 --> 00:56:06.340
there's enough density
that the carbon is visible.

00:56:06.340 --> 00:56:09.860
But as you get down to only four
coats, you can't see it anymore.

00:56:09.860 --> 00:56:13.520
What we hypothesized was that we
could train a machine learning

00:56:13.520 --> 00:56:18.050
system to understand the
patterns in the carbon

00:56:18.050 --> 00:56:20.920
that you wouldn't be able
to see with the naked eye.

00:56:20.920 --> 00:56:24.340
And here is the result from
that first experiment showing

00:56:24.340 --> 00:56:27.620
that the machine learning system
is able to amplify the ink

00:56:27.620 --> 00:56:29.820
in that fourth column even
though you can't pick it

00:56:29.820 --> 00:56:31.240
out with you eye.

00:56:31.240 --> 00:56:34.130
And here is the triptych
that shows you on the left,

00:56:34.130 --> 00:56:38.570
the original pattern for
column 4, the training sample,

00:56:38.570 --> 00:56:41.240
and then the amplification
on the right.

00:56:41.240 --> 00:56:45.600
So I call this reference
amplified computed tomography.

00:56:45.600 --> 00:56:50.280
And the idea is that you
use a set of examples

00:56:50.280 --> 00:56:53.030
of what the ink looks like
in tomography to train

00:56:53.030 --> 00:56:55.920
up a huge scale machine
learning system

00:56:55.920 --> 00:56:59.930
that it can detect
subtleties in the tomography

00:56:59.930 --> 00:57:03.180
that you cannot see
with your human eye.

00:57:03.180 --> 00:57:06.260
Reference amplified computed
tomography is actually now

00:57:06.260 --> 00:57:09.170
for me a wholesale change

00:57:09.170 --> 00:57:11.220
in the way I believe
tomography should be treated.

00:57:11.220 --> 00:57:15.060
In fact tomography is not
for you, it's not for me,

00:57:15.060 --> 00:57:18.140
it's first for the
machine learning system

00:57:18.140 --> 00:57:19.550
which amplifies what you want

00:57:19.550 --> 00:57:22.510
and then the result
is for you and for me.

00:57:22.510 --> 00:57:24.580
Here is an example
on a real fragment.

00:57:24.580 --> 00:57:30.920
The photograph on the left
shows you a lunate sigma

00:57:30.920 --> 00:57:33.010
from Herculaneum.

00:57:33.010 --> 00:57:35.490
It's real carbon ink
from Herculaneum.

00:57:35.490 --> 00:57:39.210
And on the right you see a
volume render of the tomography.

00:57:39.210 --> 00:57:43.120
And I don't think that you
can probably see the ink.

00:57:43.120 --> 00:57:47.190
Because we looked at that
and thought we'd failed, OK?

00:57:47.190 --> 00:57:49.410
Now this is what
the data looks like.

00:57:49.410 --> 00:57:51.740
And as the bar goes
left to right,

00:57:51.740 --> 00:57:54.750
you see on the right what
the slices look like.

00:57:54.750 --> 00:57:56.350
It turns out you can't
really see the ink

00:57:56.350 --> 00:57:57.650
in the slices either.

00:57:57.650 --> 00:57:59.530
You know, you'd like to be
able to see those bright spots

00:57:59.530 --> 00:58:01.920
like I showed you in
my early examples,

00:58:01.920 --> 00:58:03.220
but we just don't see that.

00:58:03.220 --> 00:58:08.030
But what we do have are
lots and lots of fragments

00:58:08.030 --> 00:58:10.630
from Herculaneum that are open

00:58:10.630 --> 00:58:13.340
and they have visible
text on the front.

00:58:13.340 --> 00:58:18.220
That visible text we believe can
form for us a reference library.

00:58:18.220 --> 00:58:20.790
The reference library from
machine learning so that

00:58:20.790 --> 00:58:23.700
when we scan, what those
look like in tomography,

00:58:23.700 --> 00:58:27.540
we can leverage that to
build a neural network,

00:58:27.540 --> 00:58:29.610
evolutional neural network,

00:58:29.610 --> 00:58:32.610
to be able to amplify what
the tomography actually looks

00:58:32.610 --> 00:58:34.070
like for ink.

00:58:34.070 --> 00:58:35.530
Here's the example.

00:58:35.530 --> 00:58:39.390
The lunate sigma
with the green box,

00:58:39.390 --> 00:58:45.260
the green box being right here,
shows the size of the test

00:58:45.260 --> 00:58:47.710
that we give to the
machine learning system.

00:58:47.710 --> 00:58:49.570
That little section we
say, take a look at that

00:58:49.570 --> 00:58:52.080
in the tomography, that's
where we think ink is.

00:58:52.080 --> 00:58:54.600
And then we also move that
box around and say, OK,

00:58:54.600 --> 00:58:56.490
here's a spot where
there's no ink.

00:58:56.490 --> 00:58:58.220
That's where we know
there's no ink.

00:58:58.220 --> 00:59:00.310
So, we have a training
system that says here's ink,

00:59:00.310 --> 00:59:03.720
here's no ink, learn
the difference.

00:59:03.720 --> 00:59:05.890
We actually do that on
a tenfold experiment

00:59:05.890 --> 00:59:07.570
which is the lower right.

00:59:07.570 --> 00:59:09.960
Ten sections, we drop one out,

00:59:09.960 --> 00:59:12.950
train on nine, classify
onto one.

00:59:12.950 --> 00:59:15.260
Because we don't have a
full reference library yet,

00:59:15.260 --> 00:59:18.750
this is the tenfold experiment
that simulates being able

00:59:18.750 --> 00:59:20.970
to have a bigger
reference library.

